\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weighted least-squares (WLS) estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
(no distribution assumption on y)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
weighted least-squares
\series default
 estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

, using a symmetric 
\emph on
weight matrix
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, is the value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{W}$
\end_inset

, which minimize the quadratic form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
({\bf y}-X\boldsymbol{\beta})'W({\bf y}-X\boldsymbol{\beta}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard matrix manipulations give the explicit result 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{W}=(X'WX)^{-1}X'W{\bf y}
\]

\end_inset

- it's an unbiased estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

, whatever the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $Var(\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{W})=\sigma^{2}\{(X'WX)^{-1}X'W\}V\{WX(X'WX)^{-1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\renewcommand{\labelenumi}{\arabic{enumi}.}
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $W=I$
\end_inset

, it reduces to the OLS estimator 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{I}=(X'X)^{-1}X{\bf y},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Var(\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{I})=\sigma^{2}(X'X)^{-1}X'VX(X'X)^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $W=V^{-1}$
\end_inset

, the estimator becomes the 
\emph on
MLE
\emph default
 (under the assumption of normal dist.), i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}=(X'V^{-1}X)^{-1}X'V^{-1}{\bf y},
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Var(\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}})=\sigma^{2}(X'V^{-1}X)^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
According to the [G-M Theorem] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gauss--Markov_theore
m), the MLE is the most efficient linear estimator for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 However, to identify this optimal weighting matrix we need to know the
 complete correlation structure of the data -- we don't need to know 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

, because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{W}$
\end_inset

 is unchanged by proportional changes in all the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Also, because the correlation structure may be diffcult to identify in practice,
 it is of interest to ask how much loss of efficiency might result from
 using a different 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When we know the correlation structure is CS (uniform/exchangable), the
 OLS is fully efficient as the WLS estimator; an intuitive explanation is
 that with a common correlation between any two equally spaced measurements
 on the same unit, there is no reason to weight measurements differently.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Using OLS estimator is misleading when 
\begin_inset Formula $V\ne I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In many circumstances where there is balanced design, the OLS estimator,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}$
\end_inset

, is perfectly satisfactory for point estimation.
 But this is not always the case.
 (example in book page 63.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Even when OLS is reasonably efficient, it is clear from the form of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Var(\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{I})=\sigma^{2}(X'X)^{-1}X'VX(X'X)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

that interval estimation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 still requires information about 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}V$
\end_inset

, the variance matrix of the data.
 In particular, the usual formula for the variance of the least-squares
 estimator, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Var(\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}})=\sigma^{2}(X'X)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $V=I$
\end_inset

, the identity matrix, and can be seriously misleading when this is not
 so.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A naive use of OLS would be to ignore the correlation structure in the data
 and to base interval estimation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}$
\end_inset

 on the variance above with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 replaced with its usual estimator, the residual mean square 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\sigma}^{2}=(nm-p)^{-1}({\bf y}-X\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}})'({\bf y}-X\tilde{\boldsymbol{\beta}}).
\]

\end_inset

